In real use of RSA there are a number of points...

The data being encrypted/decrypted (Not good terms in Asymmetric crypto)

ok lets use publicised/privatised data MUST be greater than N ^ -E 
where N is the public key. I.E. the data is less than the Eth root of N then
you can just use the eth root function to decrypt the data.

So data HAS to be padded to make it the same number of bits as N and the
normal procedure is to use 'random' padding. This stops the simple attacks 
even when the message could only have a few values.

Pete.
